A. Controls that can remain unchanged
These controls are naturally satisfied by the organization’s existing physical infrastructure, specialized security software ("Loza-1" v.2.0), operating system defaults, and established administrative workflows. They require no structural modification or additional parameterization.
•	Access Control: AC-3, AC-5 (Logical access enforcement and segregation of duties via "Loza-1" and organizational orders).
•	Audit and Accountability: AU-3, AU-6, AU-7, AU-9 (Weekly log reviews, standard OS/firewall logging content, and protection of logs via "Loza-1").
•	Configuration Management: CM-4, CM-5, CM-8, CM-12 (Impact analysis, strict physical/logical change restrictions, and the Passport-Formulary acting as a robust inventory and location registry).
•	Identification and Authentication: IA-2, IA-5, IA-6, IA-11 (Unique accounts, obscured passwords, and strict password complexity policies natively supported by Windows/Loza-1).
•	Incident Response & Maintenance: IR-3, MA-4, MA-5 (Annual IR testing; strict internal-only or escorted technical maintenance).
•	Media Protection: MP-3, MP-5 (Mandatory marking and tracking of media during transport).
•	Physical and Environmental Protection: PE-4, PE-6, PS-4, PS-5 (90-day physical log reviews by VAT "SERZHANT", physical power protection, and strict baseline timelines for personnel termination/transfer).
•	Risk Assessment & Security Assessment: RA-3, RA-7, SR-6, CA-4 (Annual risk assessments and formal risk response procedures by the SZI).
•	System and Communications Protection: SC-23, SA-3, SA-5, PL-2 (Encrypted session authentication, standard SDLC security reviews, secure storage of vendor documentation, and utilizing the Passport-Formulary as the core system security plan).
B. Controls that require parameter refinement or enhancement
These controls require the organization to enforce specific operational values (e.g., timeframes, limits) or implement technical enhancements tailored to protect data with the "Confidential" / "For official use" restriction label.
•	Access Control: AC-2, AC-4, AC-6, AC-7, AC-11 (Define termination deactivation times; restrict FortiGate routing; enforce minimum privileges; set max 5 failed logins; reduce auto-lock timeout to 15 minutes).
•	Awareness and Training: AT-2, AT-3, PL-4 (Mandate annual role-based training covering specific hardware/software; require signed "Rules of Behavior" before account creation).
•	Audit and Accountability: AU-5, AU-8 (Implement near real-time audit failure alerts for SZI/Admins; mandate internal NTP time synchronization across all hardware).
•	Configuration Management: CM-2, CM-3, CM-6, CM-7, CM-7(5) (Formalize annual baseline reviews and 1-year change record retention; implement strict "deny all" application whitelisting for authorized software).
•	Identification and Authentication: IA-3, IA-4, IA-2(1), IA-2(2) (Implement MAC filtering/802.1X on the Cisco switch; ban username reuse for 1 year; implement hardware MFA tokens for privileged accounts).
•	Incident Response & Maintenance: IR-2, IR-5, IR-6, MA-3 (Mandate 30-day initial/annual training for SZI; enforce a 2-hour incident documentation limit; require ESET AV scans for all diagnostic tools).
•	Media Protection: MP-2, MP-4, MP-6, MP-7 (Secure storage in Room 2 safes; enforce specific physical/cryptographic destruction of media; technically block unowned USBs via "Loza-1").
•	Personnel & Physical Security: PS-3, PE-2, PE-3, PE-5 (Head of Security must conduct background checks prior to access and manage the physical access/visitor lists for Room 2 and output devices).
•	Security Assessment & Planning: CA-2, CA-5, AC-1 Family (Mandate annual security assessments including physical perimeter checks; formalize POA&M creation post-assessment; enforce annual review of SZI Regulations).
•	System and Communications Protection: SC-4, SC-7, SC-10, SC-15, SC-18 (Use "Loza-1" for shared folder access; enforce "default deny" on FortiGate; set strict 15-minute network disconnects; disable remote hardware activation; block unsigned macros/scripts).
•	System Integrity & Supply Chain: SI-2, SI-3, SI-4, SI-5, SA-4, SR-3, SR-5 (Apply 30-day patching SLAs; enforce real-time ESET/FortiGate IPS monitoring; implement CERT-UA directives within 72 hours; enforce strict procurement of IT goods only from authorized Ukrainian distributors).
C. Controls for which the available information is insufficient and additional input from the system owner is required
The provided system documentation lacks the necessary details to formulate a draft decision. Clarification from the system owner is mandatory to finalize these elements of the Target Profile.
•	Access & Audit Policies: AC-12, AU-2, AU-11, AU-12 (What specific conditions trigger forced session termination? What is the exact list of audited events? What is the organizational retention period for audit logs?).
•	Remote & Wireless Access: AC-17, AC-18, AC-19, CM-2(7), PE-17 (Is the Lenovo laptop authorized for telework, travel, or wireless access outside Room 2, and what are the associated sanitization procedures?).
•	Incident Response & Backup: CP-9, IR-4, IR-7, IR-8 (What is the backup frequency, media, and encryption method? Does a formalized, standalone Incident Response Plan exist, and which exact authorities must be notified during a breach?).
•	Vulnerability & Continuous Monitoring: RA-5, RA-5(2), CA-7 (Is an active vulnerability scanner deployed? Does the organization utilize a centralized continuous monitoring strategy/SIEM beyond standard endpoint AV?).
•	Cryptography: SC-8, SC-12, SC-13, SC-28 (Are the endpoints utilizing full-disk encryption for data at rest? What specific cryptographic providers/libraries are used to protect data in transit?).
•	External Connections & Supply Chain: CA-3, SA-9, SR-2 (Does the "IT-Tour: Agency" software connect to external cloud services, and are there SLAs governing this? Does a formal Supply Chain Risk Management plan exist?).
•	Information Lifecycle: SI-12 (What are the exact legal/organizational retention and archival periods for the "confidential" travel agency data?).
